To install esphome, do this:

git clone https://github.com/esphome/esphome.git
cd esphome
git checkout dev
./script/setup

To activate the python virtual environment in a terminal shell,
do this:

source venv/bin/activate

Now after cd-ing into the growOS/esphome directory, it is 
possible to build and run esphome for CPU 0 like this:

make compile0
make upload0
make logs0

To do all three in one shot, use this command:

make run0

(see the Makefile for more commands, such as 'make update0',
which does a compile followed by an update, and make rebuild,
which rebuilds firmware for both CPU 0 and CPU 1)

The Makefile chooses a board serial number and network location
based on $USER and generates a full yaml file for esphome.
For now, only two userids (erik and maarten) are supported.
The files location.pec and location.sxm have that localization.

Once the yaml files are generated, instead of driving things
from the Makefile, it is also possible to issue esphome commands
directly on the generated yaml file, such as:

esphome compile gen_boot0.yaml
esphome upload gen_boot0.yaml
esphome logs gen_boot0.yaml

See esphome -h for more details.

Also, it is possible to connect to the growboard's IP address
from a browser to see some published information and flip
some switches.

Voila!

